0.body: Welcome to the Manic Monolith: Do It Yourself book! This book will teach you the basics of the level editor, tricks and tips, and the use of ALL the objects in the game! note The book and the game are still in heavy developement, expect some things to be slightly out of date...

132.body: Every Sign has 3 children: A String Value named "Text": Contains the text that will be shown when the level is played. A String Value named "Font": Contains the font that will be used for the text in the Sign, if the font doesn't exist, the sign won't render its text, instead it will show: "Unknown font (invalid font will be shown here)!" All valid fonts are listed in this roblox documentation page A Color Value named "Text Color": Contains the color that the text will use when the level is played.

22.body: WASD Moves the camera around Right mouse button (hold) Rotates the camera Mouse wheel Zoom in/out
22.breadcrumbs: Introduction Â» Controls Â» PC and Desktops
22.title: PC and Desktops

23.body: Thumbstick Moves the camera around Mobile has not 2, but 3 different camera control schemes! Those are: Gyroscope You move your device around in order to rotate the camera Drag screen You drag your thumb on the screen in order to rotate the camera None You cannot rotate the camera The None control scheme is intended to be used with the Drag screen control scheme, since some in-game actions like moving, rotating and resizing objects also makes the camera rotate when using the Drag screen control scheme. Mobile has no bind to zoom the camera
23.title: Mobile

24.body: Left thumbstick Moves the camera around Right thumstick Rotates the camera R1 Toggles the console mouse This feature is quite buggy and criminally untested, so if you encounter any issues, let me (Mendes) know!
24.title: Console

Level visuals Currently only contains skybox image IDs

53.body: A Vector3 value that determies the object's linear velocity. When either the X, Y or Z values are not 0, Mart's velocity will be affected by the object's velocity. The two most important interactions are as follow but others can happen depending on which values you input. Linear Velocity has the same direction as Mart's Velocity = More velocity WHILE standing on the object! Linear Velocity has the opposite direction as Mart's Velocity = Less velocity WHILE standing on the object!

54.body: A Vector3 value that determies the object's angular velocity This one is a little more complicated, and there aren't visual examples of it in action! (yet) On top of that, Mart can't interact with Angular Velocity, only unanchored objects!

63.body: Coin Groups are objects which automatically fill their volume with Coins , its recomended that you use coin groups instead of regular coins for those reasons: Performance Regular coins do a distance check every frame in order to occlude themselfes if Mart is too far away, therefore, using too much regular coins can decrease performance. Coin Groups in the other hand, do one distance check for all coins in that group. Ease of use Using Coin Groups is easier than using regular coins, since by just adjusting the size of the Coin Group new coins get created, it saves time that would've been spent CTRL + D regular coins. Level data size When using regular coins, each coin is an object, and the more objects you use, the closer you get to reaching the level data size limit. With Coin Groups, all coins in a Coin Group count as just one object. There are also A Manic Mania variant

92.body: Impulse Triggers are objects which apply a set amount of impulse to any object that touches it.
92.breadcrumbs: Objects Â» Impulse Trigger Â» Impulse Trigger

93.body: All Impulse Triggers have two children: A Vector 3 Value named "Impulse Direction": This child stores the impulse direction of the trigger, a value of 0, 15, 0 will apply impulse to any object in a upwards direction. A Number Value named "Impulse Force": This child stores the force of the impulse, higher numbers makes this trigger apply stronger impulses on objects. However you can add those respective objects in order to modify the Impulse Trigger's behavior ( remember, you have to add those objects to the Impulse Trigger yourself. They are optional. ): A Number Value named "Debounce Timer": This child stores the amount of seconds that the Impulse Trigger needs to apply another impulse (A.K.A: Cooldown) A String Value named "Sound ID": This child stores a sound ID that will be played then the Impulse Trigger gets activated by something.
